      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">May</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Maia</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman earth goddess of fertility and spring growth</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of May on the Gregorian calendar is named after a Roman goddess. Her name was <strong>Maia</strong>, and the Romans dedicated the entire month to her worship — sacrifices, festivals, and the crowning of women as her representatives on the earth.
      </p>

      <h2>Who She Was</h2>

      <p>
        Maia was a Roman earth goddess associated with fertility, growth, and the warmth of spring. The Romans called her <em>Maia Maiestas</em> — Maia the Majestic — and considered her one of the older powers, even more ancient than the better-known Olympian gods. She was sometimes paired with Vulcan (god of fire and forge) as his consort, and the priest of Vulcan offered sacrifices to her on the first of May.
      </p>

      <p>
        Her connection to spring fertility was direct. The crops were planted, the flowers were blooming, the earth was awakening — and Maia was credited with all of it. May 1 was her primary feast day. Romans held processions, brought offerings of grain and incense, and danced around decorated poles in her honor. The "May Day" celebrations and Maypole rituals that survive in some Western cultures today trace directly back to these Roman festivals to Maia.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Crediting an earth goddess for the spring growth season is the oldest form of agricultural idolatry. Yahuah Himself is the One who causes the earth to bring forth, the rain to fall, the grain to ripen, and the harvest to come in. Every page of Scripture that mentions the seasons makes this plain.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Acts 14:17</span> — "…he left not himself without witness, in that he did good, and gave us rain from heaven, and fruitful seasons, filling our hearts with food and gladness."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 11:14</span> — "I will give you the rain of your land in his due season, the first rain and the latter rain, that thou mayest gather in thy corn, and thy wine, and thine oil."
      </div>

      <p>
        The Romans took the credit Yahuah deserved and assigned it to a goddess. The credit for fertile fields, for spring warmth, for the return of growth after the winter cold — all of it belongs to the Creator who made the seasons. Naming a month after Maia gave the glory of His provision to a creature.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Like with the days of the week, knowing the name's origin matters even if the language has carried on. The fifth month of the modern calendar is named for an idol. Yahuah's calendar simply calls it <strong>Month 2</strong> (or sometimes Month 3, depending on when Aviv 1 falls in any given year), and the agricultural marker for this month is something far better than goddess-worship — <em>wheat harvest begins</em>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The harvest comes at the appointed time because Yahuah set the appointed times into creation Himself. No earth goddess is required. The earth obeys the One who made it.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        May honors an earth goddess who never created anything. Yahuah's calendar honors no one but the Creator who gave the earth its seasons in the first place.
      </div>

